## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **Medium** | 2 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called — achieving high line coverage — but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken (e.g., `UpdatePrice` doesn't change the price, `RemoveProduct` is a no-op, `ApplyBulkDiscount` applies the wrong formula).

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class follows the pattern: call method → no assertion (or trivial `IsNotNull`). This is the exact anti-pattern producing 95% coverage with zero confidence.

---

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17–21)

Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_ProductIsRetrievable()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
    Assert.AreEqual(product, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

---

#### 3. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32–36)

Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ChangesProductPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
}
```

---

#### 4. No Assertion — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39–43)

Calls `RemoveProduct` but never verifies the product is gone.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_ProductNoLongerExists()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

---

#### 5. No Assertion — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63–66)

Discards the return value entirely. Not even a trivial `IsNotNull`.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetProductCount_ReturnsCorrectCount()
{
